{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c45a71d5-5e85-4012-b457-3dec1b062e0b","content":"This repository doesn't contain documentation on that topic, but here's the general guidance:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS defaults to `/cores/`):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash** — run your NativeAOT app. macOS writes a Mach-O core file to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, check that:\n   - The directory exists and is writable: `sudo mkdir -p /cores && sudo chmod 1777 /cores`\n   - SIP (System Integrity Protection) isn't blocking it.\n\n5. **Check Console.app / `log show`** — macOS may capture crash reports under:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These `.ips` / `.crash` files contain stack traces and register state.\n\n6. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n7. **For richer .NET diagnostics**, consider using `dotnet-dump analyze` (if the dump format is compatible) or attach `lldb` with the SOS plugin.\n\n> **Note:** NativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump` because there's no CoreCLR runtime. The OS-level core dump and macOS crash reports are your primary recovery paths.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b4c048aa-ba87-49bf-99ac-679c807d0ac7","outputTokens":398,"requestId":"1BC0:1AA4EA:16265EB:18DCBE5:6A028778"},"id":"32e732fc-6d00-4ba2-9a3c-253d82b8428f","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:51:01.296Z","parentId":"9a05d04f-e6cc-4195-8516-75b4a9e38af6"}
